comment.author: 32162360@N00
comment._content: [http://www.flickr.com/photos/74004041@N06] The typeface does look like a "C". This is the "new" station built 1913 on the new duplicated line, so the "by 31/12/1905" is wrong. See History section - www.environment.nsw.gov.au/heritageapp/ViewHeritageItemDe... . I think this is pre WW1 from the people's clothes, and the embankment behind looks freshly dug with no vegetation, so I vote for 1913. Maybe even the opening of the new station? GoogleMapsSatellite

comment._content: One of the earlier stations see comments - [http://www.flickr.com/photos/state-records-nsw/3481772464/] (I seem to remember that Glenbrook railway(s) and stations history is very complicated, when trying to find out exactly where Arthur Streeton's "Fire's On" (1891) was painted - nga.gov.au/Exhibition/Turnertomonet/Detail.cfm?IRN=165173 )

comment.author: 47321757@N06
comment._content: [http://www.flickr.com/photos/beachcomberaustralia] Definitely 1913, notice that the Up track (nearest camera) is not yet open, this must be in the few months when only Down trains were using the newly opened deviation.
